``` {.sourceCode .r}
         MarkDown3 = replace_na(MarkDown3, 0),
```

**Q1**

::: {#cb19 .sourceCode}
``` {.sourceCode .r}
details_date_count <- details %>% 
  summarise(count = n_distinct(Date))

sales_date_count <- sales %>% 
  summarise(count = n_distinct(Date))

#How many more weeks of data in details compared to sales: 
details_date_count - sales_date_count
```
:::

    ##   count
    ## 1    39

> **There are 39 more weeks of data in details compared to sales**

**Q2**

::: {#cb21 .sourceCode}
``` {.sourceCode .r}
sales_date_range <- sales %>% 
  summarise(minDate = min(Date),
            maxDate = max(Date) ,
            date_range_days = maxDate - minDate +6) %>% 
  mutate (diff = difftime(maxDate, minDate, units = "weeks") + 1)

sales_date_range
```
:::

    ##      minDate    maxDate date_range_days      diff
    ## 1 2010-02-05 2012-10-26       1000 days 143 weeks

> **A2: We calculated the date range by subtracting the smallest given
> date from the largest given date, to which we added another 6 days, as
> the dates indicated the first day of the week to which the data is
> attributed.**

``` {.sourceCode .r}
# Plotting the weekly sales on a logarithmic scale by store type

sales_stores_details %>%
  ggplot(aes(x= Type,
             #we used the weekly sales log so the scale would be easier to comprehend
             y=sales_log,
             color = Type,
             na.rm=TRUE)) +
  geom_boxplot()+
  labs(title="Comparing Sales Across Store Type",
       x="Store Type",
       y="Weekly Sales (Logarithmic Scale)")
```
:::

![](data:image/png;base64,){width="648"}

::: {#cb28 .sourceCode}
``` {.sourceCode .r}
# Plotting size by store type

sales_stores_details %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x= Type, y=Size, color = Type, na.rm=TRUE)) +
  geom_boxplot()+
   labs(title="Comparing Store Size Across Store Type", 
       x="Store Type", 
       y="Size of Store by Number of Products Sold")
```
:::

![](data:image/png;base64,){width="648"}

> **We joined together information from sales and stores to inspect if
> there was any significant correlation between store type and weekly
> sales or size. We found that Type A, B, C seems to be in reference to
> the size of the store as indicated by the boxplot above. The stores
> with the largest size are categorized as Type A, the medium sized
> stores are categorized as Type B, and the smallest sized stores are
> categorized as Type C.**

**Q6**

::: {#cb31 .sourceCode}
``` {.sourceCode .r}
# Histogram to look at distribution of weekly sales. Weekly sales were negative for a few weeks so we tried looking at the distribution for only positive values. 
sales %>% 
  filter(Weekly_Sales>0) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = Weekly_Sales)) +
  geom_histogram() +
  #Added limits to view values around 0
  xlim(-10000,150000) +
    labs(title="Distribution of weekly sales",
       x="Weekly Sales",
       y="Count")
```
:::

![](data:image/png;base64,){width="648"}

::: {#cb32 .sourceCode}
``` {.sourceCode .r}
#Calculation log of weekly sales excluding negative weekly sales values
sales %>% 
  filter(Weekly_Sales>0) %>% 
  mutate(sales_log = log(Weekly_Sales)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=sales_log)) +
  geom_histogram() +
      labs(title="Logarithmic distribution of weekly sales",
       x="Weekly Sales (log)",
       y="Count")
```
:::

![](data:image/png;base64,){width="648"}

> **The distribution of weekly sales is right skewed. We then looked at
> the distribution of the log of weekly sales (only focusing on positive
> values), which gives a left skewed distribution.**

``` {.sourceCode .r}
sales_subset <- sales[sample(nrow(sales), size=100000), ]

#Method 1 - ggpairs
sales_subset %>% 
  left_join(details, on = c("Store","Date")) %>% 
  
  #We calculated the sum of dmarkdown columns (cumulative effect of different promotions)
  mutate(MarkDowns = MarkDown1 + MarkDown2 + MarkDown3 + MarkDown4 + MarkDown5) %>%
  select(Temperature, Fuel_Price, CPI, Unemployment, MarkDowns, sales_log, Weekly_Sales) %>% 
  ggpairs()
```

**Q2 - Hypothesis test to check if there is a significant difference in
weekly sales during holiday and normal weeks (excluding Thanksgiving)**

::: {#cb56 .sourceCode}
``` {.sourceCode .r}
# H0: There is no difference in weekly sales on holiday weeks compared to non-holiday weeks.
# v.s.
# H1: There is difference in weekly sales on holiday weeks compared to non-holiday weeks.


#Creating column with the holiday name:
holiday_sales_data <- sales %>% 
  mutate(holiday = case_when(month(Date) == 12 & IsHoliday == TRUE  ~ "Christmas", 
    month(Date) == 2  & IsHoliday == TRUE ~ "SuperBowl", 
    month(Date) == 11  & IsHoliday == TRUE ~ "Thanksgiving", 
    month(Date) == 9 & IsHoliday == TRUE ~ "LaborDay",
    TRUE ~ "non_holiday")) 

#Filtering out Thanksgiving rows
non_thanksgiving_sales <- holiday_sales_data %>%   
  filter(holiday != "Thanksgiving")
```
:::

Running a t-test:

::: {#cb57 .sourceCode}
``` {.sourceCode .r}
t.test(Weekly_Sales ~ IsHoliday, data = non_thanksgiving_sales)
```
:::

    ## 
    ##  Welch Two Sample t-test
    ## 
    ## data:  Weekly_Sales by IsHoliday
    ## t = 1, df = 26693, p-value = 0.3
    ## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means between group FALSE and group TRUE is not equal to 0
    ## 95 percent confidence interval:
    ##  -124  462
    ## sample estimates:
    ## mean in group FALSE  mean in group TRUE 
    ##               16012               15844

> **The t test shows that the p-value is 0.26 and t value is 1.13, which
> means that we fail to reject the Null hypothesis. The 95% confidence
> interval is \[-124,462\] which contains zero. It means that we cannot
> say that there is a significant difference in weekly sales on holiday
> weeks compared to non-holiday weeks if we exclude Thanksgiving as a
> holiday.**
:::
:::

**After analyzing the data we decided to focus on predicting the weekly
sales at a store level instead of department level.**

::: {#cb59 .sourceCode}
``` {.sourceCode .r}
#Looking at weekly sales at a store level (instead of department)
stores_weekly_sales <- holiday_sales_data %>%
  group_by(Store,Date,IsHoliday) %>%
  summarise(sum_weekly_sales = sum(Weekly_Sales))

#Joined sales, stores and details and mutated Store column to be numeric for purposes of running the regression model
model_data <- stores_weekly_sales %>%
  left_join(details, by=c("Store","Date","IsHoliday")) %>%
  left_join(stores, by="Store") %>%
  drop_na() %>%
  mutate(Store = as.numeric(Store)) %>%
  mutate(holiday = case_when(month(Date) == 12 & IsHoliday == TRUE  ~ "Christmas",
    month(Date) == 2  & IsHoliday == TRUE ~ "SuperBowl",
    month(Date) == 11  & IsHoliday == TRUE ~ "Thanksgiving",
    month(Date) == 9 & IsHoliday == TRUE ~ "LaborDay",
    TRUE ~ "non_holiday"))
```
:::

::: {#cb60 .sourceCode}
``` {.sourceCode .r}
# create a model with all explainatory variables
model_full <- lm(sum_weekly_sales ~ . , data= model_data)
msummary(model_full)
```
